      <hedline>
        <hl1>They'll Swim, Not Sink</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Henry Adler letter on Oct 17 article says bilingual education should be abandoned as a failure</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Immersion Promoted as Alternative to Bilingual Education'' (news article, Oct. 17):</p>
        <p>The United States, a country of immigrants, has never had a policy of bilingual education until the recent past.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Immersion Promoted as Alternative to Bilingual Education'' (news article, Oct. 17):</p>
        <p>The United States, a country of immigrants, has never had a policy of bilingual education until the recent past.</p>
        <p>The immigrants who came to these shores succeeded, in many cases beyond their wildest dreams, without the bilingual programs now offered. I was one of those immigrants.</p>
        <p>We learned English and adopted our new culture. Many went on to become leaders of this nation, all without bilingual education.</p>
        <p>If ''immersion'' worked well in the past, wouldn't it work well now? Obviously, bilingual education is a failure on so many fronts. It is time to revert to the reasons for the successes of previous generations.</p>
        <p>HENRY ADLER  New York, Oct. 17, 2000</p>
      </block>
